BRAZILIAN VIGNETTES
description: ''Summer Showers'' is a gentle Brazilian film with a knowing air and not so very much to reveal. It concerns an elderly man, Afonso (Jofre Soares), who retires from his job one Friday and spends the next several days regarding his own life, and the lives of his neighbors, in a whole new light. The film, which breaks down into a series of interwoven vignettes, unfolds this drama earnestly. But it lacks the spark that might make the material genuinely involving.

SCREEN:'AIRPLANE!,'DISASTER-FILM SPOOF
description: At a time when throwaway gags seem like a luxury in any film, ''Airplane!'' has jokes - hilarious jokes -to spare. It's also clever and confident and furiously energetic, and it has the two most sadly neglected selling points any movie could want right now: it's brief (only 88 minutes), and it looks inexpensive (it cost about $3 million) without looking cheap. ''Airplane!'' is more than a pleasant surprise, in the midst of this dim movie season. As a remedy for the bloated self-importance of too many other current efforts, it's just what the doctor ordered.

description: ''HOW to Beat the High Cost of Living'' is a feeble house-fly of a comedy that unsuccessfully attempts to make fun of one of the more dismaying problems of our time: inflation. It moves around erratically but it never goes any place. It's set in Eugene, Ore., a pretty, middle-sized city, and it's about the efforts of three nice young women to balance their checkbooks by robbing a shopping center.

'NO NUKES,' A MELANGE OF MUSICIANS
description: ''NO NUKES'' is a lively, likable concert movie, and it achieves its vitality without a strain. The performers, whether seen on stage or backstage or at planning meetings, mingle comfortably, and they are captured without any particular fanfare. Far from diminishing the movie's forcefulness, this low-keyed approach draws the audience close. The resulting footage is as warm as it is tuneful.

'HONEYSUCKLE ROSE'
description: THE screenplay for ''Honeysuckle Rose'' is credited to three writers, and what they have created is dialogue, not conversation. The film's four editors have put together sequences, not scenes. The direction, by Jerry Schatzberg, aims for general impressions rather than simple ones, and its only clear focus is the redoubtable Willie Nelson, who commands attention absolutely whenever he appears on screen. In Mr. Nelson's performance, and in his singing turns, the film achieves a precision in sharp contrast to the vagueness that afflicts it otherwise.

'THE BIG RED ONE,' 5 G.I.'S IN WORLD WAR II
description: SAMUEL FULLER, the director of such obsessively self absorbed, often shocking, sometimes foolish low-budget American melodramas as ''China Gate,'' ''Underworld, U.S.A.'' and ''Shock Corridor,'' has been a cult figure for years. It's ironic that just as he's being recognized as one of the great primitives of American movies, he should come out with ''The Big Red One,'' a handsome, technically first-rate, almost leisurely recollection of the World War II experiences of five American soldiers, from the landings in North Africa in 1942 until the collapse of Germany in 1945.

YERSIN'S 'LES PETITES FUGUES,'
description: It's entirely possible to admire the precision of Yves Yersin's ''Les Petites Fugues'' without responding to the film in any more heartfelt way. More than possible, it's likely. This sedate, longish Swiss film concentrates on a middle-class country household where lives are changing. The father may soon pass the farm on to his son. The daughter may begin a joyless affair with an Italian farmhand. The mother is highly responsive to everyone else's troubles. Many of these threads are woven together at mealtimes, as the family members dine in silence and exchange weighty glances.

SYBERBERGS MAD 'LUDWIG' 1972 PERCURSOR OF HIS 'OUR HITLER'
description: HANS JURGEN Syberberg's ''Ludwig: Requiem for a Virgin King,'' which opens today at the Public Theater, is a German movie that owes more to the theater, especially to German cabaret theater, than it does to the cinema. Here are a series of sketches and tableaux that, through dialogue, music and spectacle, have the function of a series of essays on the nature and meaning of the life of Ludwig II of Bavaria (1845-86), the mad king who is now remembered chiefly as the patron of Richard Wagner and as the fellow who built all those crazy castles on the Rhine.

The concert scenes capture the band, today's closest equivalent to the early Rolling Stones, in all its ragged glory. And the dramatic scenes, which amount to little more than transitional material, are mesmerizing as often as they're muddled.

HUNGARIAN' STRANGE MASQUERADE'
description: ''STRANGE MASQUERADE'' is based on the true story of a young man who, for political reasons that remain somewhat obscure in the film, is forced to disguise himself as a woman. This Hungarian film, directed by Pal Sandor and opening today at the Art Cinema, has a certain visual handsomeness and a slow, studied air. But the main thing it has is Endre Holman, a stunningly androgynous actor who looks utterly convincing in the nurse's uniform he wears throughout most of the story.
